SPECIES_COMMENTS: We came to this park because an Ovenbird had been reported five hours earlier. We both heard this bird singing clearly and loudly from 10 feet away and one of us saw the singer briefly (using binoculars) as it perched in oak branches hanging a few feet from the ground. Song was about 4 or 5 repeated phrases of tee-CHA, just like the recording we played in the car before birding the park. A branch obscured part of the bird, so that flanks and head were the only visible parts. Flank was white with dark brown spots. Edge of wing was dull brown. Face in profile showed white eye ring, dark malar stripes contrasting with white throat, and a dark stripes on side of crown. Bill long and thin and pale.

SPECIES_COMMENTS: I first saw this small (but not tiny) songbird at about 1250PM. It seemed similar in size to sparrow, but with a shorter tail. The tannish back blended in with the soil on the ground and branches of the understory of Coast Live Oaks, and was difficult to see. Originally I saw it hopping on the ground, but it flew up into an oak tree before I could view it through binoculars. Once in the tree, it froze. I was able to see dark brownish spots on its otherwise white breast. I was also able to see the thin white eye-ring which contrasted with the head which was of similar color to the back (tannish). I could see the faint border of the crown.----Alarmed by my effort to raise my lens in its direction, it loudly sang using repetitions of "tee-CHUR" which rose in volume towards the end of the phrase.----The crown stripe was bright orange with thin blackish lateral stripes. The spots on the sides of the breast converged to form streaks from the malar down along its flanks.--------

SPECIES_COMMENTS: In the sandy oak area around 9am, flitting from a snag just above a flock of other insectivores.  The first three things I noticed were its overall gray color (especially compared to a nearby Pac Slope), its small dark bill, and its strikingly short tail.  It was about the same size as the Pac Slope.  It had distinct wing bars and eye ring.  Its head gave the appearance of being a bit clunky--large and not crested.  No yellow tones were evident in either its bill or its overall color, and I saw it in good light about 6 feet away.  Some contrast between lighter undersides and darker back, but no clear white throat (as would be in a Willow).  Much smaller, shorter-billed, and shorter-tailed appearance than a pewee.
